class UndergraduateStudentProfile {
private:
    std::string fullName;
    std::string studentID;
    double gpa;

public:
    // Constructor
    UndergraduateStudentProfile(const std::string& name, const std::string& id, double gpa);

    // Getters
    std::string getFullName() const;
    std::string getStudentID() const;
    double getGPA() const;

    // Setters
    void setFullName(const std::string& name);
    void setStudentID(const std::string& id);
    void setGPA(double gpa);

    // Display student information
    void displayProfile() const;
};
```

*Highlighted section: Constructor and Initialization*

The constructor initializes the student's full name, unique ID, and GPA. It ensures that all member variables are properly assigned and validated. For instance, the GPA is constrained to a valid range (0.0 to 4.0), and the student ID must be a non-empty string.

```cpp
UndergraduateStudentProfile::UndergraduateStudentProfile(const std::string& name, const std::string& id, double gpa) {
    setFullName(name);
    setStudentID(id);
    setGPA(gpa);
}
```

*Highlighted section: Getter and Setter Implementations*

These methods provide controlled access to the private member variables. The setters include validation to maintain data integrity, such as ensuring the GPA is within a reasonable academic range.

```cpp
void UndergraduateStudentProfile::setGPA(double gpa) {
    if (gpa >= 0.0 && gpa <= 4.0) {
        this->gpa = gpa;
    } else {
        this->gpa = 0.0; // default value if invalid
    }
}
```

*Highlighted section: Display Functionality*

The `displayProfile()` method offers a clear and structured way to present the student's information, which is essential for logging, reporting, or user interface integration.

```cpp
void UndergraduateStudentProfile::displayProfile() const {
    std::cout << "Student Profile:" << std::endl;
    std::cout << "Full Name: " << fullName << std::endl;
    std::cout << "Student ID: " << studentID << std::endl;
    std::cout << "GPA: " << gpa << std::endl;
}
